posts.com:
They were one of the most competent early hardcore bands, they were extremely tight. However, they weren't very musically interesting IMO, so I like a few songs, like In My Eyes, for the dymanics, but they weren't nearly as enjoyable as more interesting bands like Bad Brains, Hüsker Dü, The Circle Jerks, or even the Germs. And the straight edge bands they influenced were IMO WAY better, like Gorilla Biscuits, and later Have Heart and Verse.

I'm from a hippie town where many of my friends and their parents were into really hard drugs, and now many of those people's lives were a mess. Because of that, I was basically straight edge until I was 20, and I'm glad I never got into anything young, because now none of that stuff sticks to me. I've smoked weed plenty of times, but I don't actually enjoy it, it's just one more thing to do when you're bored and trying to vibe at a party. I'm still very anti-hard drugs, with the exception of psychedelics, which I'm for. The dogmatism of the straight edge scene was annoying in the 00s, but it doesn't seem like militant straight edge is a thing anymore, and I think it was good to have a philosophical strain in punk/alternative music that told people to be thoughtful about what they were doing to themselves and other people.

>>114181679
Most politically genuine and musically creative of all the international scenes.

Bérurier Noir started in squats in the Paris suburbs. When 'Concerto pour détraqués' came out they became punk superstars, so they needed a security team composed of the Paris' Redskins, a group of left-wing skinheads, some professional martial artists. The French punk scene in the 80s was one, if not the most violent in Europe and maybe the world, because of the tensions between far-right skinheads or thugs and multicultural France and the left-wing world of culture at the time backed by the Socialist Party.
You're making fun of us because you're dumb, okay. But French punk was one of the most important cultural scene of Europe since its inception, and almost every French artist is influenced by the punk initiative of the 80s. It was the first major counter-culture of the country and stays relevant due to its unusual experimental sound that influenced electronic music and alternative rock.

It was predominantly recorded on Audacity on a computer with a Yamaha DM-105, one track the guitars were recorded with this 4 track mixer/interface thing instead, fl studio was used for drums with no effects and slight EQ and reverb on the guitar tracks, two phones were used to record parts via phonecall, some samples come from shortwave radio, the tracks would be rendered at a low bitrate and then amplified until they start clipping, keyboards were recorded with my half bro holding the mic at the speaker. This album was very influenced by James Ferraro - iAsia.

In USA, it's not uncommon for people to be unfamiliar with classical music, or to have trouble distinguishing between different Scandinavian countries. However, that doesn't mean that the influence of classical music on electronic music subgenres in these countries should be overlooked.

In the case of dungeon synth, a subgenre of electronic music that originated in the 1980s and 1990s, it's interesting to consider the distinct musical influences that have shaped its development in different parts of Scandinavia.

For example, in Sweden, it's been suggested that the keyboard and organ music of ABBA, the iconic Swedish pop group, had a significant influence on the development of dungeon synth in the country. ABBA's music is known for its catchy and upbeat sound, and it's not surprising that it would have an impact on other musical genres.

On the other hand, in Norway, it's been suggested that the music of composer Grieg had a greater influence on the development of dungeon synth. Grieg was a 19th century Norwegian composer known for his romantic and nationalistic style, and his music often featured prominent piano and orchestral elements.

While these two examples may seem quite different at first glance, it's worth noting that the use of organs and keyboards is a common feature in both ABBA's music and dungeon synth, and it's possible that this shared element contributed to the influence of ABBA's music on Swedish dungeon synth.

Overall, it's fascinating to consider the various musical influences that have shaped the development of different subgenres of electronic music, and how these influences can vary from one country to another.

>>114148670
there's not really a right or wrong way to music. if people like the song, you did it the right way. there's lots of "rules" for producing, but rules are made to be bent and sometimes broken entirely. me personally, i only use like 3 fx on my master fx chain. less is more imo.

i'd say get really good at getting great sound with 3 basic plugins. EQ, Compression, and Reverb. those are like salt pepper and garlic. i don't think there's an album made since 1950 that DIDN'T use those fx. They're essential. practice getting good sounds from just those three, the branch out. that's just my opinion.

>>114148670

here is your masterclass:

1. never put anything on master, ever, leave that for... mastering.
2. high pass literally everything, but do so subtly; too much will remove the character of the sound.
3. add subtle saturation/distortion to all of your busses. yes, really, everything. subtle distortion generates upper harmonics, which means you can get away with carving off more low end to make room in the mix without losing the sound of the track. (make sure you apply distortion BEFORE eq'ing however)
4. use busses/groups to group and effect similar tracks.
5. use LCR mixing; double (or triple) tracking takes and panning them hard R/L (and center if you're triple tracking) is a really powerful technique that generates good stereo image; be careful of phase though, and monitor in mono to make sure compatibility is good.
6. use compression; use it basically everywhere. learning how to dial in a compressor is an art, and should be done in a subtle way.
7. use parallel processing. this ties in with the last point. every bus should have a rack of effects in parallel (in ableton, this is called an "Audio Effect Rack"). in general, each rack should have 1. a clean signal 2. a compressed signal, and 3. a 100% wet reverb signal. you can of course add other effects. generally speaking, my busses typically look like: distortion -> EQ -> parallel processing rack described above.
8. use targeted bell filters in your EQ to bring out instruments in your mix; make sure different part don't have the same frequency ranges accentuated however.

digesting and internalizing this will get you a long, long way. some people may disagree with certain parts of this, but this is the stuff i wish i knew a very long time ago.

!!!!!!!!REAL ANSWER!!!!!!!!

The garage rock revival replaced nu metal and post-grunge. The garage rock revival's promotion was literally a reaction against how dumb post-grunge and nu metal felt. Bands like The White Stripes, The Vines, The Hives, Yeah Yeah Yeahs, and post-punk revivalists like The Killers and Franz Ferdinand felt cool because they actually had style and weren't these dorky, greasy aggro mallrat bands. It only lasted a couple years in the US, though, and then it gave way to the pop punk/emo-pop bands. Which is for the best, because while those bands were fun, in the UK it gave way to pale imitations - the "landfill indie" bands like The Kooks, who were painfully lame.

Note I selected the bands I did because they were the ones that got a lot of MTV play, not because of quality. The White Stripes and Yeah Yeah Yeahs were great, but it's a shame The Libertines weren't bigger here.

An optical prism is a transparent optical element with flat, polished surfaces that are designed to refract light. At least one surface must be angled — elements with two parallel surfaces are not prisms. The most familiar type of optical prism is the triangular prism, which has a triangular base and rectangular sides. Not all optical prisms are geometric prisms, and not all geometric prisms would count as an optical prism. Prisms can be made from any material that is transparent to the wavelengths for which they are designed. Typical materials include glass, acrylic and fluorite.

A dispersive prism can be used to break white light up into its constituent spectral colors (the colors of the rainbow) as described in the following section. Other types of prisms noted below can be used to reflect light, or to split light into components with different polarizations.

Quite possibly the most dogshit documentary I have ever watched

Ken Burns and Wynton Marsalis have the most traditional, absolute dogshit views on jazz in the history of humanity. I truly cannot believe I sat down through all of this over the course of a week. It’s absolutely abhorrent.

Basically, 9/10 episodes here focus on maybe the most boring periods of jazz. Yes, they were very important and necessary and I would’ve gladly sat through 5 episodes of it and have the last 5 cover 50s jazz onwards, but that’s not what happens. Instead all jazz past the 60s is shoved into a single episode.

A 19 hour jazz documentary where quite possibly the most creative period of musical history is shoved all into one episode. Not only that, it is treated like a joke.

It seems the creators of this documentary think that the swing shit is the pinnacle of jazz and the ultimate form of creation. The innovators of the late 50s through 70s are not only hardly mentioned but ripped to shreds.

It treats free jazz like it’s a joke. It treats spiritual jazz like it’s a joke. It treats any form of the avant garde like it’s a joke. It’s like if my racist great grandpa made a documentary on jazz. “Oh that old stuff with the funky beats was the good ol days, but when the music started getting political, that’s when I tune out.” type shit.

This shit is a fucking joke and to anyone who watched this with no knowledge of jazz I apologize for this shit having to be your source of knowledge for this absolutely amazing and beautiful genre. Ken Burns should never have touched jazz with a ten foot poll.

And just for good measure, I must stress one more time

Fuck Wynton Marsalis.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114183756
Ken Burns has always had an unfortunate habit of giving his consultants a huge amount of leeway in shaping the narrative of his documentaries. It's probably most egregious in The Civil War where his primary advisor and interviewee was some eccentric novelist (not even a historian lmao) who shilled for Lost Cause myths, which significantly narrowed and sanitized the scope of the series; and more recently it turned up in Country Music where his reliance on testimony from Nashville veterans led to an over-emphasis on country as a monolithic mainstream industry and insular community centered around totems like Music Row and the Oprey, while majorly important artists and scenes elsewhere in the country are either skimmed over or completely ignored.
With Jazz, having Marsalis, Crouch and Murray as his main consultants was a horrifically shortsighted choice. Bringing in three of the most infamously stubborn bop and swing purists in jazz criticism was always going to guarantee that avant-garde and fusion would be almost totally marginalized and the decades since the free jazz and fusion revolutions would get the same treatment as an in memorium reel at an awards show, giving the impression that jazz is dead or irrelevant and genteel in the same way classical is perceived.

The fact that so many books still name Taylor Swift as "the greatest or most significant or most influential" pop star ever only tells you how far pop music still is from becoming a serious art. Jazz critics have long recognized that the greatest jazz musicians of all times are Duke Ellington and John Coltrane, who were not the most famous or richest or best sellers of their times, let alone of all times. Classical critics rank the highly controversial Beethoven over classical musicians who were highly popular in courts around Europe. Pop critics are still blinded by commercial success. Taylor Swift sold more than anyone else (not true, by the way), therefore she must have been the greatest. Jazz critics grow up listening to a lot of jazz music of the past, classical critics grow up listening to a lot of classical music of the past. Pop critics are often totally ignorant of the pop music of the past, they barely know the best sellers. No wonder they will think that Taylor Swift did anything worthy of being saved.

In a sense, Taylor Swift is emblematic of the status of pop criticism as a whole: too much attention paid to commercial phenomena (be it grunge or U2) and too little to the merits of real musicians. If somebody composes the most divine music but no major label picks him up and sells him around the world, a lot of rock critics will ignore him. If a major label picks up a musician who is as stereotyped as can be but launches her or him worldwide, your average critic will waste rivers of ink on her or him. This is the sad status of pop criticism: pop critics are basically publicists working for major labels, distributors and record stores. They simply highlight what product the music business wants to make money from.

At such a time, pop critics will study their rock history and understand which artists accomplished which musical feat, and which simply exploited it commercially. Taylor Swift's "Aryan" music removed any trace of country from her art. It replaced soulful Americana with linear corporate melody, and youthful teenage attitudes with smug valley-girl petulance.

Contemporary musicians never spoke highly of Taylor Swift, and for good reason. They could never figure out why her' songs should be regarded more highly than their own. They knew that she was simply lucky to become a pop phenomenon (thanks to the Kanye West incident, which had nothing to do with her musical merits). Nothing else grants Taylor more attention than, say, Zola Jesus. Not to mention the far greater musicians who followed Taylor in the subsequent decade or the country musicians themselves who initially spearheaded what Taylor Swift merely later repackaged to the masses.

Taylor Swift sold a lot of records not because she is the greatest musician but simply because her music was easy to sell to the masses: it had no difficult content, it had no technical innovations, it had no creative depth. She wrote a bunch of catchy 3-minute ditties and she was photogenic. If Kanye West had not interrupted Taylor at the 2009 VMA awards, you would not have wasted five minutes of your time reading these pages about such a trivial artist.

Genesis to Revelation is folkpop and very Moody Blues inspired
Trespass and Nursery Cryme continue this folk sound but a lot more proggy and I think more somber. Really cool British storytelling
Foxtrot and Selling England by the Pound are equally proggy but also very theatrical, incorporating elements of genres like music hall. That description may sound similar to Lamb Lies Down, but they focus on British storytelling like their earlier albums and the folk sound is still there

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114109205
From Genesis to Revelation is Moody Blues-inspired folkpop
Trespass and Nursery Cryme are where they get more proggy but still within the folk realm. A lot more somber in my opinion. Wonderful storytelling. Their most underrated stuff
Foxtrot and Selling England By The Pound is still similar to their other stuff but a lot more theatric (using elements of music hall for example), their classical music inspiration being a lot more upfront as well, and more rock-oriented (psychedelic rock and of course progressive rock), but still within their British folk roots as far as overall sound and storytelling/lyricism goes. This is the fan favorite era.

Yeah, Japan's a nation of avant-prog and brutal prog and prog metal.
While they do have traditional progressive rock, it's usually very derivative, there's not a lot of truly notable Japanese traditional prog groups. Experimental/avant/brutal prog stuff is where Jap prog really shines but it can come off as overly indulgent and unlistenable.

Even when Tatsuya Yoshida formed Koenji Hyakkei with the intention of being less inaccessible compared to Ruins, more in line with Magma and wearing its influences from bands like Gentle Giant and Genesis on its sleeves, it's still way too much for a lot of Western prog fans.

posts.com:
“Progressive fusion rock” is the best I could come up with for a short title, but here’s something better to capture what I mean!I am looking for a drummer and keyboardist with good ears who find joy in the challenge of developing almost any musical motif into something pleasing. They will confidently draw on their ear, inspiration, skill, and creativity to add whatever they believe fits regardless of genre. The motif itself may be as simple as a major melody or comfortable four chord progression, or as complex as a five-chord progression in 7/16 in the double harmonic scale... though I don't expect it'll hit that point very often. There will be a general emphasis on rock only to the extent that the music should generally (though not exclusively) have some sort of rock-like edge – be it in distortions / instrumentation, dynamics, or simply thematic content – but all genres are welcome (hence, fusion!).The music we will make will be diverse and possibly without direction at first but will still sound good at any given instant. The hope is that our individual musical histories and biases will work their ways in to provide an overall sound and/or direction over time as our chemistry develops.The ideal candidate:
- enjoys challenging themselves stylistically
- prides themselves on being able to find the feel within "complex" music
- can generally execute on their instrument what they hear in their head (some trial & error is fine!)
- knows enough music theory to be able to communicate ideas
- is inspired by music that exhibits a tasteful blend of multiple genres
- has a vehicle
- is a kind, respectful, down to earth, and professional individual

For me I focused on learning each box of the pentatonic scale and getting it down to muscle memory, then the next box, and on until I had the entire scale in all positions memorized. Before all this I literally just played by ear (meaning I played random notes and hoped they went together, or played the same stale things i always played)

posts.com:
>>114179074
>How do you adjust pickup height on direct mounted humbuckers?
There are screws on either side of the pickup. Pickup will be held up by foam normally. Surgical tubing around the screws is the repairman's preferred alternative to foam as it lasts longer and holds the pickup in place better. They're mounted with long screws to allow for the this. The height adjustment screws on P90s are right in the middle of the pickup between the pole pieces.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114180701
>With tubing and foam I can't picture a way to adjust height up, only down, compressing the tube/foam
The point of foam and tubing (and springs for that matter) is they expand and hold the pickup at a higher position when you loosen the screws. That is your up adjustment. Springs normally have that extra bracket because they dig in to the wood if you just put them around the mounting screwes.
